diff:1618174781:1618174781:=1,38d0%0a%3c :Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a%3c :Expansion: Personal reflection on "only"%0a%3c :Author: sanjana_m%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.TheUseOfOnlyInIndianEnglish|TheUseOfOnlyInIndianEnglish]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.AnanyaV|AnanyaV]]%0a%3c :Section: D%0a%3c :Completed: 11.04.2021 - 13:59%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c When I was younger, I used to travel to India every few years to visit my family, and I found that I was often subconciously switching some constructs I used. One example is the way I used "only." At first, going into stores and saying things like "I only will take that one," which to me meant that I would only buy that one thing, was actually interpreted like "I am the one who is going to get that item." Once I started to realize this, I became aware of how I was using certain words, and essentially just switched the way I talked to say things like "I only cleaned the dishes", meaning that I was the one who cleaned the dishes, not my sister. Then, coming back home and using "only" like this caused some confusion with my friends, which is when I realized that that construct is mainly used in Indian English. After an older cousin explained to me that the way the word is used is different in the US and India, I knew to switch the way I talked based on my environment.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:Category:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
